nucleate cells containing keratin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratinocytes connected by desmosomes\u003C/strong\u003E are the defining feature of the stratum spinosum. These strong protein connections give the cells their characteristic \u0027spiny\u0027 appearance under microscopy and provide mechanical strength to the epidermis.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlattened cells containing keratohyalin granules\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the stratum granulosum, which lies above the stratum spinosum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColumnar cells undergoing mitosis\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the stratum basale, which lies below the stratum spinosum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECells filled with melanin pigment\u003C/strong\u003E - While melanin transfer occurs here, this better describes melanocytes in the stratum basale\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnucleate cells containing keratin\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the stratum corneum, the outermost layer of the epidermis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stratum spinosum also contains Langerhans cells, which are dendritic cells that play an important role in skin immunity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The stratum spinosum is the second deepest layer of the epidermis, containing keratinocytes connected by desmosomes.","Desmosomes provide mechanical strength to the epidermis by linking adjacent keratinocytes.","Langerhans cells in the stratum spinosum provide immune surveillance for the skin."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"it